main event: Unidentified radar targets were detected by the Westover AFB approach control radar on January 24, 1951.
interesting points: The radar targets were not picked up by any other radar in the area, including the Westover GCA radar.
The report suggests the targets were likely caused by a B-47 aircraft carrying a radar beacon, though no definitive explanation is provided.
Several pilots and radar technicians observed the incident, but no photographs or physical evidence were obtained.
The fighter squadron at Westover AFB was unable to intercept the targets due to mechanical difficulties.
The Westover approach control radar was designed to detect targets up to 150,000 feet and 40 miles away, and could pick up targets moving less than 20 miles per hour.
witnesses: Pilots, radar technicians, and approach control personnel
